## The process by which the light of photons from [[Unsorted/The Sun\|The Sun]] is converted into bioavailable chemical energy by [[Unsorted/Life#Autotrophs\|autotrophic]] lifeforms

## Equation
$$6CO_2 + 6H_2O + Light\hspace{0.2cm}Energy â†’ C_6H_{12}O_6 + 6O_2$$

Plants need
- Light
- Water
- CO<sub>2</sub>

- Phosphorous
- Glucose

#### Light and dark reactions
- Light reactions produce glucose
- Dark reactions produce energy from glucose via [[Unsorted/Respiration\|Respiration]]

## Factors
- Temperature
	- Enzymes work best between 15-35Â°C
- Light
	- Bright light speeds up, low light speeds it down
- Water
	- Must have adequate moisture
	- Water quality can influence it
- CO2 levels
	- High levels speed up, low levels slow down

## Types
- C3 Photosynthesis
	- CO2 intake goes directly into cells to do photosynthesis
	- Common in areas where there is significant water and mild temperature
		- Because they suffer heavily from [[Unsorted/Transpirational loss\|transpirational water loss]]
	- Includes most plants, all trees
		- Soy, oats, wheat, rice, fruit trees, most broadleafed plants
- C4 photosynthesis
	- CO2 intake and photosynthesis are *spatially* separated
		- Have specialized cells called 
	- Have cells which incorporate CO2 into 4-carbon compounds
		- Similar to how hemoglobin holds oxygen?
	- ![Pasted image 20220906191030.png|300](data:image/png;base64,)
	- Grasses, such as corn, sugarcane, spinach
- CAM photosynthesis
	- CO2 intake and photosynthesis are separated by *time*
	- Stomata are only opened at night
		- Lose much less water because of cooler temperatures
	- But don't grow as fast
	- Pineapple, cacti, succulents

![Pasted image 20220906191448.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)


## Chloroplasts
- Double-layered lipid membrane
- Stroma
	- Watery liquid containing DNA, ribosomes, and enzymes
- Granum: Stacks of thykaloids
	- Thykaloids: internal membranes which perform photosynthesis
		- Flat hollow membranes covered in interconnected disks arranged in stacks
		- Many layers of thykaloids are stacked on top of eachother
		- Covered in photosynthetic reaction centers
		- ![Pasted image 20221109115333.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
	- Lamellae
		- Connecting tubes between thykaloids that make the membrane continuous
